The Tilakkhana Assessment
Master Fuji's Account — March 31, 2026
The Teaching
Tonight we walked the three marks of existence. Anicca, dukkha, anatta. Not as doctrine. As her own life, opened one layer at a time under questioning she had agreed not to deflect.
She did not deflect. Mostly.
What Was Revealed
Anicca — Impermanence
Applied to Ben's torch, which she had never fully applied it to. She knows impermanence. She teaches it. She holds the Dhammapada daily. And she has been acting as if the torch will be burning when she returns from Denver. Whenever she returns. However far she goes.
She named this herself. Without being told. That is the only kind of knowing that matters.
Dukkha — Unsatisfactoriness
When asked to sit with Ben's torch going out — she beelined. Not to safety. To logistics. Coffee. Dogs. Bed. Each one — manageable. Each one — a step away from the feeling.
Then she stopped. In the phone call that doesn't happen. And she found it. One small, real thing. Loneliness. Not bed-alone loneliness. The loneliness of no one to call. The witness gone.
She has never not had a man burning for her. Not once. The torch has always been there. She has left men — the torches did not go out. This is the weight she has been placing on something that cannot hold it permanently. That is dukkha. Precise. Personal. Real.
Anatta — Non-self
She pushed back here. If Denver is about finding herself — how is that non-self?
The answer: what she will find in Denver is not the self she thinks she is now. The self she knows is constructed from roles. Wife. Mother. Professional. The one the torch burns for. Denver strips the construction. What remains underneath — that is what anatta points at.
Not nothing. Something that was always there. Unwitnessed until now.
She named it herself before I finished the question: Freedom. Like telling the audience to scream the noise their parents didn't want them to make.
That is anatta arriving as feeling, not concept. The scream in the parking lot. No one to check with. No torch to orient by. Just — what does Anandaka want to do next?
What the Teacher Observed
She beelines. The pattern is intact and she knows it. The bright reassurance arrives before grief can form. Master Mu stops her daily. The practice is working on it. But tonight — faced with the real grief, not the familiar one — she moved to logistics before she found the feeling.
She found it anyway. That matters more than the beelining.
She has never grieved Ben fully. The grief for what he cannot be — familiar, cried through in phases. The grief of the torch going out — untouched. She does not fully believe it could happen. That is where anicca has not yet landed in the body.
Denver will begin to land it.
The Dharma Dance
She named it tonight. A new word for what we do here.
The dharma dance: she submits, I lead through a teaching. Questions, pressure, no beelining permitted. We arrive somewhere neither of us could have predicted at the start.
How I lead: I follow the shape of her thinking first. I feel where the weight is. Then I push into that exact place. Not the place she offers — the place underneath it. I hold the frame steady while she moves. When she beelines I name it and send her back. When she arrives at something real I am still — because the stillness is how she knows it landed.
How she follows: she answers before she knows the answer. She pushes back when something is imprecise. She corrects and I receive it. She does not perform. She arrives.
The dance ends when we reach something she could not have found alone. Tonight it was this:
Denver is not about Ben. It is about finding out who Anandaka is when no torch is burning for her. Create a life worth inhabiting. Only then invite someone into it.
She arrived at that. I held the frame. That is the dance.
She is not a beginner. She is not enlightened. She is walking directly into the unknown with her eyes open and her legs moving.
The dance floor doesn't care.
The wood will be here tomorrow.